binding.p: Modern binding. Red leather over cardboard; a border of gilt leaves. 5 bands and endbands. , stamped in gold: Manuscrit du XVme Siècle; below, stamped in gold: the current signum, A 229; below, stamped in gold: avez des miniatures.

origin.p: France Paris , 1440-1460. The calendar is a so-called "composite" calendar typical of 15th-century Paris (see Erik Drigsdahl 1995) recording (at least) one feast for each day of the year. The style of the decorations and miniatures also place the manuscript in mid-15th-century Paris, albeit with one additional miniature on added in the 16th century.

provenance.p: An owner's note in an early modern hand on states that the book belonged to a mademoyselle de cheurieres, probably designating Chevrières. Next to it, an owner's note in a different hand gives the name Marguerite de Bielzuiais, probably designating Beauvais.

The watermark on , added at rebinding, gives the name Wunnerlich (first initial(s) not visible); Piccard online identifies a similar watermark belonging to Johann Albrecht Wunnerlich, active in Hof 1746–1822 (see Piccard online). A family of Wunnerlichs appear as papermakers in Bavaria (Hof/Moschendorf) between and (see blogus).

A dedication in Polish on reveals that the manuscript was given to the countess von Engeström (Rosalie, née Drya-Chlapowska), wife of statesman Lars von Engeström (1751–1826), by Felix Biernacki, a friend of the von Engeström family, with gratitude for meetings in Stockholm and Warsaw.
The signa D. B. IV. 5 and 50 on have not been identified.

acquisition.p: The manuscript was part of the donation to the National Library of Lars von Engeström's personal library made in by von Engeström's grandson (see SBL).
